<subSubSection id="A8D5656DA707D66B798D6E24DE884346" pageId="11" pageNumber="89" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E07036E6A707D66B798D6E24DE744311" blockId="11.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="11" pageNumber="89">
<heading id="BB38818AA707D66B798D6E24DE744311" bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="11" pageNumber="89" reason="3">
<emphasis id="D2BBEAF4A707D66B798D6E24DE744311" bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="11" pageNumber="89">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E07036E6A707D66B798D6E1ADE884346" blockId="11.[188,1399,311,372]" pageId="11" pageNumber="89">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="27CF4D65A707D66B7A2B6E15DC5E4363" authorityName="Satkunanathan &amp; Benjamin" authorityYear="2022" box="[795,878,312,337]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Carrhotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atratus">
<emphasis id="D2BBEAF4A707D66B7A2B6E15DC5E4363" box="[795,878,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="89">atratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ meaning ‘darkened’, loosely referring to its blackish body colour.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
